<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-399-696  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 399 696.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Design  August 9 1990 v38 n15 p89(7).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Low-skew clock drivers maximize MPU systems. (microprocessorunit)(includes related articles) (Design Applications) (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hanke, Chris; Tharalson, Gary.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Maintaining synchronous complex-instruction-set computer orreduced-instruction-set computer microprocessor systems requiresthe use of low-skew clock drivers that provide well-controlledclock signals.andP;  Clock drivers generally have one input and severaloutputs.andP;  Three specifications define clock-driver skew: thedifference between the fastest and the slowest propagation delaysbetween outputs, the difference between the high-to-low and thelow-to-high transition for outputs, and the maximumpropagation-delay delta between pins.andP;  Designers must consider thedifferences in clock microcomputer-board trace length and loadingwhen computing total system skew.andP;  Clock traces must be terminatedto ensure a clean clock signal.andP;  The two best termination schemesfor clock lines are Thevenin termination and ac termination.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ClocksMicroprocessorsCircuit DesignMethodsTimingSignal PropagationIntegrated circuitsNew TechniqueTiming Circuitry.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   RISC 88000 system board-layout section. (chart)Calculation of system skew. (chart)Common termination techniques. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>